paragraphs.text: An informal, friendly term to address a group of people, regardless of gender
Guys, we’re going to be late if we don’t leave now. [audio:phrases_verbs_guys_3]
An expression to show alarm or concern, especially when something goes wrong
Oh no. I locked my keys in my car! [audio:phrases_verbs_oh_no_2]
(link xx) See more uses of 'Oh no'
Said when you realize something that you didn’t notice or forgot about
I need to get milk from the store. Oh, and I need to get eggs, too. [audio:phrases_verbs_oh1_2]
Said to show enthusiastic approval of a suggestion or plan
Luke: Oh, it’s happy hour at Jay’s Bar. Should we go there? [audio:phrases_verbs_great_idea_2]
To plan an informal and casual meeting
Let’s meet up for coffee this week. [audio:phrases_verbs_meet_up_2]
We’re going to meet up with friends tonight. [audio:phrases_verbs_meet_up_3]
Of course you can stay at my place! You don’t even have to ask. [audio:phrases_verbs_of_course_2]
Pailin: Can I make myself another cup of coffee? [audio:phrases_verbs_of_course_3]
Said when a person is in your specific city or location for a short stay
My parents are in town this weekend, so I won’t be free. [audio:phrases_verbs_in_town_2]
Since you’re in town, we should catch up. [audio:phrases_verbs_in_town_3]
ฉันเลี้ยงเอง
Let’s get coffee. Don’t worry, it’s my treat. [audio:phrases_verbs_its_my_treat_2]
Since you’re visiting, the tickets are my treat. [audio:phrases_verbs_its_my_treat_3]
ฉันก็คิดอย่างนั้น
Pailin: Is Sebastian majoring in Psychology? [audio:phrases_verbs_i_think_so_2]
Luke: Do you have a band-aid by any chance? [audio:phrases_verbs_i_think_so_3]
Pailin: I think so, let me check my bag.
These can be said when you’re not bothered by something, or they can be a gentle way to say ‘no’ or to decline something
Luke: Sorry, I forgot to bring you that book you wanted to borrow! [audio:phrases_verbs_thats_okay_2]
Pailin: That’s okay, I’m not in a rush to read it.
Luke: Do you need help carrying that? [audio:phrases_verbs_thats_okay_3]
Pailin: It’s okay. It’s not heavy.
ติดตาม กดติดตาม
I’m not following him on Instagram. [audio:phrases_verbs_follow_2]
Do you follow Jeff on TikTok? [audio:phrases_verbs_follow_3]
Very informal expression used for disappointment
Aw, some birds pooped all over my car! Man, and I just got a car wash, too. [audio:phrases_verbs_man_2]
The common way to ask what someone’s job is
So, what do you do in Thailand? [audio:phrases_verbs_what_do_you_do_2]
When used by itself as a verb, with no beverage mentioned, it’s often understood that it’s referring to alcohol
I like to work out in the morning. [audio:phrases_verbs_work_out_2]
(link xx) See more uses of ‘Work out’
To go out and do small tasks on your to-do list
I’m exhausted. I’ve been running errands all morning. [audio:phrases_verbs_run_errands_2]
I’ll be back in about 2 hours. I’ve gotta run some errands. [audio:phrases_verbs_run_errands_3]
Drop off [someone or something] / drop [someone or something] off
To take someone or something to a particular place and leave them there
I’ll drop off the kids at soccer practice on my way to work. [audio:phrases_verbs_drop_off_2]
Could you drop these letters off at the post office for me? [audio:phrases_verbs_drop_off_3]
Pick up [someone or something] / pick [someone or something] up
To go somewhere to collect a person or a thing
I have to pick my daughter up from daycare by 6PM. [audio:phrases_verbs_pick_up_2]
I’ll be leaving the airport soon. I’m just waiting to pick up my suitcase.  [audio:phrases_verbs_pick_up_3]
Said when everything works out well
Pailin: I’m off work at 5. How about you? [audio:phrases_verbs_perfect_2]
Luke: Perfect, I’m off at 5, too. Let’s meet at the subway station at 5:30.
Luke: How about I bring the pasta, and you bring the wine. [audio:phrases_verbs_perfect_3]
Pailin: That’s perfect. I’ll be at your place at 6 then.
Can be said to agree with what someone says
Pailin: That movie was so good! [audio:phrases_verbs_i_know_2]
Luke: I know! The acting was incredible.
Pailin: I hate this gloomy weather. [audio:phrases_verbs_i_know_3]
Luke: I know, it makes me depressed.
(link xx) See more uses of ‘I know’
ตื่น / ปลุก
I keep waking up in the middle of the night. [audio:phrases_verbs_wake_up_2]
My kids woke me up this morning. [audio:phrases_verbs_wake_up_3]
Everyone was dancing, so I decided to join in. [audio:phrases_verbs_join_in_2]
We’re playing volleyball, do you want to join in? [audio:phrases_verbs_join_in_3]
What were your favorite subjects to study in school?
